Executive Summary
The U.S. Department of Defense (DoD) is the federal executive department responsible for the nation's military forces and national defense. While the Department of Veterans Affairs primarily serves veterans after military service, the DoD is responsible for administering military operations, training, readiness, active-duty personnel management, and many transition programs that prepare service members for civilian life.

Understanding the DoD is important because many veteran benefits begin with military records, discharge documentation, and programs administered before separation from service.

Mission
The Department of Defense exists to provide the military forces needed to deter war, defend the United States, and support national security objectives.

Primary Responsibilities
The DoD is responsible for:

Military readiness

Active-duty operations

National defense

Personnel management

Military training

Military healthcare during service

Military education and professional development

Transition assistance

Maintaining military service records

Military Departments
The Department of Defense includes the military departments responsible for organizing, training, and equipping their respective service branches.

These include:

Department of the Army

Department of the Navy

United States Navy

United States Marine Corps

Department of the Air Force

United States Air Force

United States Space Force

The DoD also includes numerous defense agencies and combatant commands.

Why This Matters to Veterans
Many programs veterans use later in life originate with the Department of Defense.

Examples include:

DD Form 214

Service treatment records

Military personnel records

Security clearance history

Transition Assistance Program (TAP)

SkillBridge

Credentialing Opportunities On-Line (COOL)

Tuition Assistance (while serving)

These records often become essential when applying for VA benefits after separation.

Important Programs
Transition Assistance Program (TAP)
Helps service members prepare for civilian life by providing:

Career planning

Resume assistance

Employment resources

VA benefits briefings

Financial planning

Education guidance

SkillBridge
Allows eligible service members nearing separation to participate in civilian internships, apprenticeships, or training programs while still serving.

Military OneSource
Provides free support services including:

Financial counseling

Relationship counseling

Education resources

Transition support

Tax assistance

Relocation guidance

Defense Finance and Accounting Service (DFAS)
Handles:

Military pay

Retired pay

Tax documents

Survivor benefit payments

Financial records

Veterans may need DFAS records when verifying military service or retirement-related information.

Defense Health Agency (DHA)
Responsible for administering the Military Health System, including healthcare for active-duty personnel and many military beneficiaries.

Medical records created during military service can later support VA disability claims when relevant.

Relationship with the Department of Veterans Affairs
Although they work closely together, the DoD and VA have different responsibilities.

Department of Defense	Department of Veterans Affairs
Active military service	Veteran services
Military operations	Disability compensation
Military healthcare	Veteran healthcare
Personnel records	Veteran benefits
Transition programs	Long-term veteran support
Many veterans interact with both agencies during the transition from military to civilian life.

Who Uses DoD Resources?
Depending on the program, DoD resources may be available to:

Active-duty service members

National Guard members

Reserve members

Military retirees

Military families

Transitioning service members

Eligibility varies by program.

Frequently Asked Questions
Is the Department of Defense the same as the Department of Veterans Affairs?
No. The DoD oversees the U.S. military and active service, while the VA administers benefits and services for eligible veterans after military service.

Can I still use DoD resources after leaving the military?
Some programs end upon separation, while others—such as access to military records or certain transition resources—may still be available. Eligibility depends on the specific program.

Why is my DD Form 214 connected to the DoD?
The DD Form 214 is issued by the military at separation from service and serves as one of the foundational documents used when applying for many veteran benefits.

Common Misconceptions
"The DoD handles VA disability claims."
Incorrect. VA disability claims are administered by the Department of Veterans Affairs, although military service and medical records maintained by the DoD may be important evidence.

"Once I leave the military, I never need DoD records again."
Incorrect. Service records, personnel files, training history, and discharge documents are often needed throughout a veteran's lifetime.

